{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1c1c2978-cd54-4616-8e9e-4151b27b5dda","content":"For .NET 8 on Windows, **`dotnet-trace`** is the best starting point — it's lightweight, .NET-aware, and doesn't require VS or PerfView installed.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds is usually enough)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need OS-level detail too (kernel + managed stacks):\n\nUse **PerfView** instead:\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\nPerfView captures both managed and native call stacks, which is better for diagnosing thread pool starvation, GC pressure, or native interop issues.\n\n### Which to pick?\n\n| Scenario | Tool |\n|---|---|\n| Pure .NET code hotpath | `dotnet-trace` |\n| GC / thread pool / native interop | PerfView |\n| Production, minimal overhead | `dotnet-trace` |\n| Need flame graphs | Either → export to `.speedscope` |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2065a430-9ac0-4a3c-a220-c1cb620744a1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code change request.","outputTokens":398},"id":"b0f0e895-38bc-4ff0-a075-365b9adf0026","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:48:55.006Z","parentId":"f46b3b2b-7966-4a26-aac1-372acb34257a"}
